facts.value:
William Bocock was born 29 February 1796 in Market Rasen, Lincolnshire, described by Charles Dickens as the “sleepiest town in England.” He was christened 9 March 1796 at the parish church, Market Rasen St. Thomas the Apostle. Just nine days after the baptism of her first child, Mary Maltby, wife of John Bocock, died and was buried in the St. Thomas churchyard. Four years later on 10 July 1800, John Bocock married Mary Dove and six more children were born to them.
When John Bocock, William’s father, died in 1818 at the comparatively early age of 45, William most likely was able to support himself. He was married for the first time 12 June 1820 at Scawby St. Hybald, Lincolnshire, to Hannah Dixon, daughter of John Dixon, who had been identified as the toll collector at Peckfield Bar, Ledsham, Yorkshire, when she was christened in 1792. Peckfield “was once a notable spot on the Great North Road” from London to York.
This match seems to have provided William with the inspiration for an occupation as well as a wife. Or perhaps the occupation led him to his wife? For the rest of his life, William moved from toll bar to toll bar on the British turnpike system, supplementing his earnings as a toll collector with shoemaking. Roads in England had historically been the responsibility of each local parish, although this worked a hardship on the people who lived in sparsely populated areas with rough terrain. Many roads in Britain were not publicly financed, however, but built or maintained by private turnpike trusts individually authorized by an Act of Parliament. In 1825, in the early years of William Bocock’s career, about 1,000 trusts controlled 18,000 miles of road in England and Wales, but even then the turnpike system comprised only about a fifth of British roads, with the rest maintained by parishes. 
A turnpike trust would usually be responsible for about 20 miles of roadway and would collect tolls from long-distance coach travelers, freight wagons, and livestock drovers.  Not all who used the turnpike had to pay a toll. For example, according to a local history of the Brentford High Street, “pedestrians, the royal family, soldiers on the march, post horses carrying mail, church goers on Sunday, funeral processions, carriages on election days, carts carrying road mending materials, agricultural implements or manure and horses going to water all passed through the gates free.” A toll collector, or pikeman, either bid for running a toll gate or was hired to do so. The toll collector and his family typically lived in small cottages provided by the trust. These toll cottages often had front bays where the toll collector could observe the road and the traffic. William Bocock had become a pikeman at the peak of the turnpike system.
William and Hannah Dixon Bocock’s first child, Joseph Bocock, was christened 18 February 1821 and died later that same year. Because Joseph’s christening was also recorded in non-conformist records, this event provides evidence of the family’s religious affiliation. Although William Bocock observed the requirements of the established church (along with everyone else before the advent of civil registration), the family’s religious associations were among the non-conformists, most likely Wesleyan Methodist. 
William and Hannah’s next child, Mary Ann Bocock, was born later the same year, and her 13 December 1821 christening record also appeared in non-conformist records, as did the 25 March 1824 christening of her younger brother, Thomas Bocock. Up to this point, the young family has been living in Market Rasen. 
With the birth of their daughter, Jane Bocock, 30 December 1824, the family was recorded as living at Newstead Toll Bar, Lincolnshire, on the eastern approach to Stamford in the southwestern corner of Lincolnshire. Although they worshipped at Barn Hill Wesleyan Methodist Chapel in Stamford, when Jane died at 18 months, she was buried at Uffington just east of Stamford where her burial is recorded in the parish register. (Non-conformists had few burying grounds and were dependent on the established church for burials.) John Bocock, their last son, was born 1 January 1826, also at Newstead Toll Bar. Later that year, Hannah Dixon Bocock died at Scawby, where she had been married and where she had family to care for her. She was buried in the St. Hybald’s churchyard 26 November 1826. William was left a widower at 32 with three surviving children, the oldest barely five years old.
One year later on 15 November 1827, William remarried at Balderton, Nottinghamshire. His new wife, Hannah Winks, had been born in 1800 at Cowbit, Lincolnshire, a daughter of William Winks and Mary White. Their first child, a son, William Winks Bocock, was born 27 February 1829 at the Balderton Gate Toll House. His mother did not long survive his birth, dying 17 April 1829 in Balderton, leaving William a widower once more but now with four small children to support and care for, including the new baby.
William must have looked within his Methodist community for a wife. He found a new companion in Sarah Brough, now 31 years old and living in nearby Nottingham. Sarah, born 5 April 1799 in Mansfield, Nottinghamshire, the daughter of James Brough and Jane Bowskill, had been orphaned at the age of six, with little known about her life between her mother’s death and her marriage. William and Sarah were married at Nottingham St. Mary the Virgin 26 April 1830, both signing their names to the marriage register.
Their first daughter, our Hannah, undoubtedly named for William’s deceased wives, was born 22 February 1831 at the Balderton Gate Toll House, located on the approach to Newark-on-Trent on the Great North Road between London and Edinburgh. The Toll-Bar House no longer stands at No. 261, London Road (but two photos of it can be seen on flickr.com). Sarah Bocock, their second daughter and mostly likely named for her mother, was born 24 June 1832, also at Balderton. However, when Sarah was two years old, she contracted smallpox and was left blind. 
Almost five years later, the family was living at Tinsley Toll Bar, east of Sheffield, when Elizabeth Bocock was born 11 May 1837, a few weeks before the beginning of civil registration in England and Wales. The Tinsley Toll House was situated on Sheffield Road, at the junction with Dead Man’s Hole Lane (which led to a ford), in an area sometimes called Templeborough, close to the boundary of the Tinsley and Rotherham parishes. The Toll House stood on the right-hand side of the tree- and hedge-lined road and on the Sheffield side of the gates. It was a square, whitewashed, two-story cottage with the typical bay window. The whitewashed “weigh house” was on the south side of Sheffield Road. 
When their next child, Samuel Bocock, was born 27 January 1841, William was listed as a shoemaker on his son’s birth certificate and residing at Oakwell in Barnsley. But six months later, when the first 1841 U.K. census was taken, William, now 45, was listed as toll collector at the Oak Well Bar. Sarah had responsibility now only for William Winks (12), Hannah (10), Sarah (8), Elizabeth (4), and Samuel (listed as S’l), who was four months old. 
Mary Anne, William’s oldest daughter by his first marriage, had gone into service and she was found in Caistor, Lincolnshire in the same 1841 census. She would later marry Robert Procter Smith and they would live in Gainsborough with their children. The older sons were on their own and doing well. At a house warming many years later 30 December 1908, Elizabeth told her assembled family that their Grandfather Bocock was known for his honesty and integrity and that “his employer valued him so highly that he persuaded my three brothers to leave their places of employment and take high positions of trust in his service. They, through their good salaries dependability and good habits became independently rich.”  The brothers indeed all prospered as agents for a glass manufacturer. Thomas married Sarah Cundell and John married her sister Ann Cundell, daughters of Robert and Mary Cundell of Rotherham. William Winks Bocock never married and died intestate. The distribution of his estate relieved the poverty of his younger sisters’ families, for which they were very grateful.
When Emma Bocock, the youngest of William Bocock’s children, was born 27 June 1843, he was the toll collector at Broadfield Bar on the southwestern approach to Sheffield, the Nether Edge. The city of Sheffield is situated in a shallow bowl with roads radiating in all directions. The toll road through Broadfield Bar ran from Sheffield to Owler Bar with the name of the toll bar taken from the nearby Broadfield plantation or estate. The Toll House where the family lived was located on Abbeydale Road nearly opposite the junction with Belper Avenue. The house was built about 1812, used until 1875, and demolished a decade later. (The City of Sheffield has several copyrighted images of the Broadfield Toll Bar cottage in its online collection at picturesheffield.com.)
While Emma was still a toddler, Samuel died 11 March 1845 of hydrocephalus. Samuel had been affectionately called the Prophet Samuel because he loved to preach, but when he died, his name appears on the certificate as William. Was it a mistake, or did his father want one last remembrance? That he loved to stand on a chair and preach suggests that the family spent enough time at chapel so that he had someone to imitate. The family was back at the Oak Well Toll House in Barnsley, but William was listed as a shoemaker on the death certificate. The Oakwell area was more industrial than Abbeydale Road. Although still rural, it was surrounded by glassworks, coal mines, their outbuildings and equipment. Samuel was buried at Barnsley St. Mary the Virgin church field.
(Continued in Stories)

facts.value:
Charles Law
(1832-1862)

Charles Law was born at Felkirk, South Hiendley, Yorkshire, England on December 19, 1832.  His parents were Isaac Law and Mary Grayson.  Little is know of his earlier years, so this sketch begins with him as a young man.  Charles was a shoemaker by trade and was very skillful and proficient.  He could look at a fancy shoe and then reproduce one almost exactly.  By just measuring a person’s foot, he made a perfect fit.  However, this business was not too profitable.  Everything required in his trade—leather, thread, etc.—had to be purchased with money and his customers mostly paid for their shoes and repair work with produce.  Times were hard and the lack of money caused him to become very restless.  He began selling tea as a sideline.  Tea was always in great demand in England and the extra income helped out.  

During his traveling and selling, he chanced upon one of the street meetings conducted by the Mormon elders.  One being Orson Pratt. He attended, became interested, and was baptized on December 2, 1855. He continued traveling and selling tea, and was so enthusiastic about his new religion that he preached the Gospel wherever he went, and was made a traveling Elder.  While selling tea at the home of William Bocock, he met three Bocock sisters who had recently lost both parents.  They were Hannah, Elizabeth, and Emma Bocock.

Their father had been a tollgate keeper at the Barsby Toll bridge, where a toll was charged for people, vehicles, and animals before they crossed the bridge.  The bridge itself was also a scale used in weighing livestock, produce, etc.  After their father’s death, the three girls operated the tollgate and made most of their living by it.  However, all three were well educated and had learned the art of hat making and trimming.  Hannah was a schoolteacher as well and Emma did the housework.  It was at the tollgate that Charles preached the Gospel and converted these young women.  They were baptized on March 25, 1857.  

It soon became the main desire of the four to come to Zion and mingle with the Saints.  At that time, Charles was the father of two children. He had them on the ship, along with his wife Maria Robinson, but fate intervened and the children broke out with an erruptable disease (most likely chicken pox or smallpox).  The ship’s officers would not let them remain on board, their money was refunded, and they left along with their mother.

Charles and the three Bocock sisters left Liverpool, England on March 28, 1857 on the ship “George Washington.”  They landed in Boston on April 20, 1857.  Most of the Saints left immediately for Utah but some remained in the East to earn enough money to make the trip.  Charles Law and the Bocock sisters were among those who remained.  They came to Utah in the Company of Captain William G. Young and arrived in Salt Lake on September 26, 1857.  Charles married Hannah Bocock on October 2, 1857, shortly after reaching Salt Lake, and on January 31, 1858, he married Elizabeth.

About this time, news was announced that Johnston’s army was on its way to Utah to annihilate the Mormons.  President Young, knowing of their treachery, ordered all of the people out of the city while the army passed through.  Charles, his two wives, and their sister Emma went to Springville, Utah.  Instead of returning to Salt Lake, Charles acquired an acre and a fourth of land at Second South and 2nd East and they remained in Springville.  Charles built an adobe home for his three wives. Clay was handy for making sun dried adobe.  Beds were made with outposts and cross boards.  Cord or small ropes were run both ways. They were tightened, and sprinkled with water and how they'd tighten up.  (Sleep tight).

August 31, 1861, he took his three wives to the Endowment House in Salt Lake and had them sealed to him for time and all eternity.  He had three children by Hannah—Hannah Moriah, Fredrick William and Isaac Brough.  By Elizabeth he also had three children—Charles Orson, Sarah Elizabeth, and Jacob Theodore.  He had two children by his youngest wife Emma—Frances Jacob, and a baby girl that died.  They were all born in Springville.

Charles had built a nice adobe house that faced south for his wives.  All three wives lived in the same home, but each had her own private room and place for her children.  They had one large gathering room, and a cooperative kitchen.   Charles had his workshop in the home also.  It was large enough for his bed, a shoemaker’s bench, and other pieces of furniture.  He continued his trade as a shoemaker, but once again became restless, as he always did when he could not seem to get ahead.  When the gold rush was on in California, he went to California in hopes of making more money.  In this instance, no good ever comes from disregarding the advice of the Lord’s prophets.  President Young had told his people to stay home and care for their families.  Charles did not find what he expected!  His health gave way and he returned home a broken down man.  He died about a year later of consumption (probably emphysema) at age 29 on September 20, 1862 and was buried in Springville, Utah. 

After his death, his wives lived and worked together.  A great love always existed among the three sisters.  The children of each wife were taught to obey the other two who almost seemed like mothers to them.  Hannah taught school, and the other two resumed their trade of hat making and trimming.  If one sister was rushed with her work, the other two helped out.  They lived in love and harmony until each of them married again, and they were divided and went their separate ways.  Hannah married John James Humphreys on July 1, 1864.  Elizabeth married Fredrick Weight on July 1, 1865.  Emma married Alma Moroni Blanchard in 1864.

contributed by Bonnie Furniss Forsyth
Sources of information for this history are from the history of Charles Law and Emma Bocock by Francis J. Law as well as research done by Darlene Law and other family members.

Charles Law was a slim built, narrow shouldered man, about 5 feet 8 inches tall.  His eyes were an ordinary, clear blue and his hair, an auburn, and inclined to be curly. Just to look at him one would say his whiskers were black, but let the sun shine on them and they were then seen to be a chestnut or deep cherry red or brown.  He had very fair skin and one man who saw him said that he was the whitest faced, black whiskered man he'd ever seen.  He stood up straight, but was rather drooped shouldered, not square.  In his prime he never weighed over 140 pounds.  He was quick as lightning in his movements.  He was a very energetic, and industrious man.  He couldn't tolerate idleness.  Before he attempted to do anything, he would figure out just what it would cost, and whether he could make it or not.  He never nagged, but his chldren understood that his word was law.  He took an active part in the church and community, until his death.
